		<h2 style="margin-top:10px;">Experiment 2 : Boost Converter</h2>
		<br>
		<strong>Concept</strong>
		<p>
			DC-DC Converters are power electronics circuits that convert a dc input voltage to a different dc output voltage level.
		</p>
		<center>
			<img alt="banner-buckConverter" class="img-responsive" id="headerMainImage" src="~/images/experiments/buckConverter/banner.jpg">
			<p>Figure 1: A buck converter on a printed circuit board</p>
		</center>

		<!-- Start drop-down Advantages DC-DC -->
		<p>
			<a class="collapsed" data-toggle="collapse" href="#advantages-dcdc">
				<span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right"></span>
				Advantages of DC-DC Converter
			</a>
		</p>
		<div class="collapse" id="advantages-dcdc" style="height: 0px;">
			<ul>
				<li>High efficiency.</li>
				<li>Smaller components and less thermal management.</li>
				<li>Output voltage can be either higher or lower than the input voltage.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
		<!-- End drop-down Advantages DC-DC -->
		<!-- Start drop-down Theory -->
		<p>
			<a class="collapsed" data-toggle="collapse" href="#theory">
				<span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right"></span>
				Theory
			</a>
		</p>
		<div class="collapse" id="theory" style="height: 0px;">
			<p align="justify">
				A boost converter’s output voltage is always higher than the input voltage. Figure 2 shows the schematics of a boost
				converter. It has a dc input voltage, a transistor working as a switch, an inductor and a capacitor forming a low pass
				filter to smooth out the output voltage, and a load resistor. The diode provides a path for the inductor current when
				the switch is opened and is reverse biased when the switch is closed.
			</p>
			<center>
				<img alt="fig2-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig2.jpg">
				<p>Figure 2. Schematics of a boost converter</p>
			</center>
			<p>When the switch is closed, the diode is reverse biased. The equivalent circuit is shown in Figure 3.</p>
			<center>
				<img alt="fig3-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig3.jpg">
				<p>Figure 3. Equivalent circuit when the switch is closed</p>
			</center>
			<p>When the switch is open, the diode is forward biased. The equivalent circuit is shown in Figure 4.</p>
			<center>
				<img alt="fig4-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig4.jpg">
				<p>Figure 4. Equivalent circuit when the switch is open</p>
			</center>
			<p>
				Output voltage of a boost converter is controlled by a pulse width modulated (PWM) signal. The duty cycle is the ratio
				between the on time and the switching period shown in (1). By adjusting the duty cycle, we can obtain desired output
				voltage, which is shown in (2). When D increases, the output voltage increases. When D decreases, the output voltage decreases.
			</p>
			<br />
			<center>
				<img alt="fig5-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig5.jpg">
				<p>Figure 5. Duty Cycle</p><br />
				<img alt="fig6-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig6.jpg">
			</center>
			<p align="justify">
				If the inductor current is continuous, the boost converter is operating in continuous conduction mode. If the inductor
				current is reduced to zero, the boost converter is operating in discontinuous mode. We would like to keep the boost
				converter operating in continuous conduction mode. The minimum inductance to keep the boost converter in continuous
				conduction mode is the critical inductance. Value of the critical inductance is shown in (3).
			</p><br />
			<center>
				<img alt="fig7-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig7.jpg">
			</center><br />
			<p align="justify">
				Another basic DC-DC converter is buck-boost converter shown in Figure 6. The output voltage of a buck-boost converter
				can be either higher or lower than the input voltage. Ratio of the output voltage over the input voltage is shown in (4). If
				D>0.5, the output voltage is greater than the input voltage. if D < 0.5, the output voltage is less than the input voltage.
			</p><br />
			<center>
				<img alt="fig8-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig8.jpg">
				<p>Figure 6. Buck-boost converter</p><br />
				<img alt="fig9-boostConverter" class="img-responsive" src="~/images/experiments/boostConverter/fig9.jpg">
			</center><br />

		</div>
